      <div id="news" class="wide"> 
        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Colette Irwin-Knott to Retire from Umbaugh</h1>
          <span class="date">By Umbaugh Announcements, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "" != ""},{/if} November 19, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1cknott.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/cknott.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>​How does 33 years go by so fast? And how does a retiree still look so young?</p>

<p>  Colette Irwin-Knott will retire from Umbaugh at the end of the year. She has not only been the knowledgeable and calm advisor for bond issues for countless school districts, public libraries and other municipalities, she was literally a pioneer at Umbaugh. </p>

<p>  Colette was employee number eight in a firm that now numbers more than 80. She was the first woman professional on the staff, the first professional hired with a business degree instead of a CPA, and the first female partner. “I’m proud of the exciting professional women’s initiative we launched to help women in their careers,” said Colette. Many other women have since taken client service leadership roles at Umbaugh, and even more have been identified as “up and comers.”</p>

<p>  “While Umbaugh has grown significantly in the time I’ve been here, I’m pleased to say we still hold true to our key core values, and our culture is still very much that of a close-knit organization.”</p>

<p>  “Colette’s influences are woven into the fabric of firm. She has defined our firm’s culture and values and will no doubt be with us each day for many years to come,” said Gary Malone, partner.<br />
 <br />
 Of all of the projects Colette has advised, the $694 million Indianapolis Public Schools Capital Improvements Program from 2001 to 2013 and the Indianapolis-Marion County Public Library Central Library project are the ones she considers the most significant and memorable. </p>

<p>  But she doesn’t overlook the importance of smaller projects: “I’ve also taken great pleasure in working on funding for $250,000 library and school renovations and additions. I grew up in a small community and understand how important these projects are. Often times, this is the most significant capital improvement for decades to come.”</p>

<p>  Another career highlight was serving as president for the National Association of Independent Public Financial Advisors (which recently became the National Association of Municipal Advisors or NAMA), during a turbulent time as the industry was reacting to increased regulation and scrutiny.</p>

<p>  “Having grown up in Argos, Indiana, I never imagined in my wildest dreams I would someday meet with SEC commissioners one-on-one in Washington, D.C. to represent the nationwide interests of the public finance industry.”<br />
 <br />
 Colette quietly announced her intent to retire about a year ago, allowing adequate time for a transition. She said, “We’re making sure the transition goes smoothly so clients can feel confident of our continued commitment to excellent service.”</p>

<p>  She describes the last few months, though, not as coasting – but as a sprint to the finish: “I have this mental picture of being a marathon runner with hands held over my head and kicking into high gear as I see the finish line in sight.”</p>

<p>  With their sons now young adults, Colette and her husband, Gary, are looking forward to more time for adventure travel, including return trips to Greece where they spent their honeymoon and to the national parks of southern Utah. You may or may not know that the Knott family traveled to Spain a few years back for the running of the bulls. Gary and their sons gave the bulls a run for it, while the ever-practical Colette says she sat on the sidelines saying silent prayers. The family has also been known to zip line over the rain forests of Costa Rica, so relaxing vacations are not the norm for them. </p>

<p>  When asked if she’ll miss her work at Umbaugh, Colette says: “I will miss coming back from a public hearing knowing I was part of something bigger and more significant, and I will miss the wonderful people I’ve worked with all these years.”</p>

<p>  Best wishes on your retirement, Colette. We will miss you!</p>
